question.title: How do I call a Java static method with no arguments in Clojure?

node.contents: Object/getClass is not a static method. Call it on an object.

astNode.text: Object/getClass is not a static method. Call it on an object.

node.contents: I am trying to figure out how to call a static method with no arguments in Clojure. Two (bad) examples are (sun.misc.Unsafe/getUnsafe) and (Object/getClass), both of which throw a CompilerException caused by a NoSuchFieldException.

node.contents: Yes I know there is a simpler way to call getClass and I should not be using sun.misc.Unsafe at all - just wondering how to call a no-arg static method in Clojure in general.

node.contents: Getting at an Unsafe instance involves overcoming some access restrictions. The simplest way is to use reflection; see the Java Magic. Part 4: sun.misc.Unsafe blog post by Mykhailo Kozik for a description of this and other methods. Here's a Clojure snippet which does just that:

astNode.text: Getting at an Unsafe instance involves overcoming some access restrictions. The simplest way is to use reflection; see the Java Magic. Part 4: sun.misc.Unsafe blog post by Mykhailo Kozik for a description of this and other methods. Here's a Clojure snippet which does just that:

elements.contents: (let [f (.getDeclaredField sun.misc.Unsafe "theUnsafe")] (.setAccessible f true) (.get f nil)) ;= #<Unsafe sun.misc.Unsafe@63124f52>

units.rawText: (let [f (.getDeclaredField sun.misc.Unsafe "theUnsafe")] (.setAccessible f true) (.get f nil)) ;= #<Unsafe sun.misc.Unsafe@63124f52>

node.contents: As pointed out by acomar and WolfeFan, getClass is not a static method -- it's an instance method declared by Object and therefore available on all objects:

elements.contents: (.getClass the-unsafe) ; the-unsafe obtained as above ;= sun.misc.Unsafe

node.contents: As for the actual question, (Foo/meth) is the correct syntax for a no-argument static method call in Clojure.
